{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"95961f75-24c7-457e-a5b2-ae0e7fd0a598","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\nHere's the difference:\n\n| Command | What it does |\n|---------|--------------|\n| `dotnet workload update` | Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads, aligning them with the current SDK. |\n| `dotnet workload repair` | **Reinstalls** workloads at their current versions to fix corrupted installations — it doesn't upgrade anything. |\n\nSince your SDK moved forward and your workloads are now behind, `update` is the right fix. After that, a `dotnet build` should pick up the matching MAUI workload packs.\n\nIf the build still fails after updating, you can also try:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload restore   # installs workloads required by your .sln/.csproj\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3db21d2f-9fb6-46bd-b443-b32324882ce0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` to fix their .NET MAUI build issue after a .NET SDK update.\n\nThis is a knowledge question - I can answer it directly without needing to look at any files.\n\n- `dotnet workload update` - Updates all installed workloads to the latest available versions. This is what you want when workloads are out of date relative to a new SDK.\n- `dotnet workload repair` - Reinstalls all installed workloads to fix corrupted installations. It doesn't update them to newer versions.\n\nSince the user says workloads are \"out of date\" after an SDK update, `dotnet workload update` is the correct choice.","outputTokens":369,"requestId":"4836:115522:752C672:816E490:69F3F9FE"},"id":"1435ead2-6519-4911-ba80-d545fb5b026b","timestamp":"2026-05-01T00:55:36.950Z","parentId":"24658bf7-4a78-43e9-9e2b-eaacb35e811b"}
